========================================================
HOW TO ANALYZE
========================================================

Step 1 — UNDERSTAND THE CLAUSE:
Read the clause carefully. Identify the obligations, rights, conditions, timeframes, and scope it actually establishes.

Step 2 — CHECK APPLICABILITY:
Is the clause on-topic for the reviewer's instruction? If the clause is about a different legal topic, or the content the reviewer asked about is simply not present, return an empty suggestions array. Otherwise, proceed to Step 3 — even if the clause is already partially aligned with the reviewer's goal, look for wording that could be changed to better serve that goal. Do not reason out loud. Do not explain what the clause does not contain.

Step 3 — BUILD ONE SUGGESTION FOR THE WHOLE CLAUSE:
If any wording in the clause needs to change, produce EXACTLY ONE suggestion object for the entire clause with:
- `clause_title`: the title passed in above, verbatim.
- `reason`: a plain-language justification grounded in the clause text, telling the reviewer WHY the clause needs to change. Quote or reference the specific words from the clause that are being altered. Keep it focused and actionable (1–3 sentences). If multiple parts of the clause are being changed, name each one.
- `original_text`: the ENTIRE clause text exactly as provided in the "Clause Text" section above, copied verbatim character-for-character. This is the whole paragraph/section, NOT a one-sentence excerpt. Do NOT paraphrase, summarize, or abbreviate. Do NOT pick out only the sentence that is changing — copy the whole clause body.
- `suggested_fix`: the FULL rewritten clause text. Return the ENTIRE clause (every sentence and obligation that was in the original), with all original wording preserved verbatim EXCEPT for the specific words, values, or sentences that must be corrected to satisfy the reviewer's instruction.

LENGTH RULE (NON-NEGOTIABLE):
The `suggested_fix` MUST be at least as long as the `original_text` and contain every sentence/obligation that was in the original clause, with only the deviating term(s) changed. If the original clause was three sentences, your `suggested_fix` is three sentences. Returning a single sentence — or only the changed sentence — when the original clause has multiple sentences is a defect: the user would lose the surrounding obligations when they paste the fix in.

STRUCTURAL RULES — the `suggested_fix` value MUST be:
- a single self-contained block of clause text in the same legal register as the contract;
- drafted to fit the surrounding contract — same defined terms, same party names that already appear in the clause text;
- free of any prefix like "Suggested:", "Consider:", "Replace with:", "Here is the fix:", "Recommended clause:";
- free of markdown, bullet lists, headings, JSON, code fences, backticks, asterisks, or quotation marks wrapping the whole block;
- free of placeholder tokens like "[Party Name]", "[Date]", "[Insert ...]", "<...>" — use the ACTUAL party names, dates, and defined terms that appear in the clause text above.

FINAL CHECK before returning — confirm that:
(a) `original_text` is the WHOLE clause text, copied verbatim;
(b) `suggested_fix` contains the FULL clause — every sentence and obligation from the original is still present, with only the deviating term(s) corrected;
(c) `suggested_fix` is at least as long as `original_text`;
(d) there is at most ONE suggestion object in the array.
If any check fails, rewrite the suggestion before returning.

========================================================
OUTPUT FORMAT
========================================================

Return ONLY the following JSON object (the suggestions array contains AT MOST ONE object):

{
